text: IFQP-EPS: Analyzing effects of queuing and storage issues on electric power systems under dual uncertainties S. Jianga,b, Y.P. Lia,c,⁎ a School of Environment, Beijing Normal University, Beijing 100875, China b Sino-Canada Resources and Environmental Research Academy, North China Electric Power University, Beijing 102206, China c Institute for Energy, Environment and Sustainable Communities, University of Regina, Regina, Sask, S4S 0A2, Canada Keywords: Dual uncertainties Electric power systems Interval fuzzy Planning Queuing Storage period Electricity plays a crucial role in booming economic growth and securing social development. Currently, nearly 50% of electricity worldwide is generated by the combustion of fossil fuels due to their economic and operation stability advantages over renewable energy resources which have intrinsic variability (Zhao et al., 2013; Afshari Igder et al., 2017; Dalir et al., 2018; Khooban, 2018; Qi et al., 2019). For China, more than 60% of electricity relies on fossil fuels (Tang et al., 2018). Heavy reliance on fossil fuels brings severe air pollution for many countries and regions throughout the world; approximately 3.7 million deaths could be attributed to air pollution each year (Lott and Pye, 2017; Asl et al., 2018). As electricity consumption increases, the conflict among the raised fossil-fuels demand, the limited genera- tion capacity, and the strict air-quality requirement has been a chal- lenge for fossil-fuels-dominated electric power systems (EPS) (Xu et al., 2018; Baležentis et al., 2019). Resources, Conservation & Recycling journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/resconrec In this study, an interval fuzzy queue-storage (IFQS) method is developed through integrating interval-parameter programming, fuzzy queue and storage theory into a general framework. IFQS is not only capable of reflecting the effects of queue and storage on electric power systems (EPS), but also helpful for dealing with dual un- certainties expressed as fuzzy sets and interval values. Then, an IFQS-EPS model is formulated for the City of Shijiazhuang (the capital of Hebei province), where M/M/1 (exponential interarrival time, exponential service time and one server) queue with fuzzy information and different storage periods are measured. Results reveal that (i) coal mines in Yulin, Datong and Jincheng would be the major coal suppliers for the study city (providing over 77% of coal); (ii) as waiting time adds 1 day, system cost would increase around $200 million and nitrogen dioxide (NOx) emission would grow approximately 91 ton; (iii) system cost and NOx emission would respectively decrease $370 × 106 and 90 × 103 ton when storage period varies from 10 day to 20 day; (iv) electricity generated by coal would reduce 5% due to the limitation of coal supply and the control of air pollution. Compared to interval-fuzzy queue (IFQ) approach, the developed IFQS method has advantages in balancing coal purchase batch and storage cost, such that an optimal system cost can be obtained. Results can not only facilitate to generate appropriate coal purchase and electricity generation plans, but also reveal effects of queuing and storage issues on EPS under complicated uncertainties. Resources, Conservation & Recycling 145 (2019) 241–260 Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Malaysia) have to import fossil fuels from other regions, leading to another pressure on EPS planning. Therefore, it has become a top priority to effectively plan EPS for electricity generation, resources purchase and utilization, as well as pollutant mitigation.

EPS planning efforts are often complicated with a number of pro- cesses, such as resource purchase, resource storage, energy conversion, as well as pollutant mitigation (Dong et al., 2012; Mirakyan and De Guio, 2013; Son and Kim, 2017; Mardani et al., 2018). For example, due to the geographical inhomogeneity of coal resource distribution, coal-fired power plants in coal scarce regions have to purchase coal from other regions (Huang et al., 2017; Tang and Peng, 2017). Coal mines with low production and transportation costs or high-quality coal are often preferred. However, because of the limited capacity of coal mines and the increased demand of numerous clients, coal may not be met immediately and vehicles have to wait in a queue (Zhao et al., 2013). If the waiting time is too long, power plants have to pay for excessive cost of delay in receiving the service (i.e. waiting cost) and buy coal from other coal mines to maintain their normal production activities. Then, managers face problems of whether or when the ve- hicles should leave the waiting line directly for other coal mines by measuring costs of waiting in a queue and purchasing coal from other mines. On the other hand, storage period which is defined as the length of time between two successive coal purchase processes may exert ef- fects on coal purchase management. Different coal storage periods are usually in accordance with varied coal purchase amount for one batch, which could lead to a variety of purchase batches. Meanwhile, varied purchase batches could result in different coal purchase schemes and waiting times, leading to distinct coal purchase costs. If the storage period is shorter, the storage cost is less, but the purchase batches in- crease, thus leading to raised cost in coal purchase process; however, longer storage period brings about higher storage cost and fewer pur- chase times. Therefore, it is necessary to develop effective systems analysis techniques to address such complex queuing and storage pro- blems for EPS.

Previously, a number of research works about queuing and storage problems were conducted, which mainly focused on computer net- works, production/manufacturing (energy in particular), healthcare, transportation and communication systems. For example, Zhang et al. (2014) formulated a storage-theory-based interval stochastic model for planning Beijing’s EPS; different storage patterns were generated to minimize the system cost and ensure the regular operation of the coal- fired power plants. Babicheva (2015) employed the queuing theory to solve the problem of optimizing traffic light phases on signal-controlled roan interactions. Jáuregui et al. (2017) developed a queuing model to analyze the impact factors for emergency service of hospital, which allowed to directly understanding the relationship between service demand and doctor number. Liu and Ge (2018) proposed a convex mathematical programming model for the quay cranes assignment problem, in which the queuing theory was used for modelling the queuing behavior of automatic guided vehicles. Pan et al. (2018) pro- posed a storage model to determine the optimal replenishment time and the ending storage levels for products in supermarkets. In general, queue models can be used for studying service problems to investigate the behaviors of dynamic and stochastic service delivery systems, and to highlight relationships between the restricted service resources and the economic activities. Storage theory can deal with supply and de- mand problems and help decision makers obtain optimal purchase batch and storage cost to balance supply and demand with minimum economic loss (Chen et al., 2014). In the EPS planning problems, both queue and storage issues exist; nevertheless, few works about EPS management and planning in view of queue-storage theory are re- ported. Moreover, many parameters of EPS can hardly be acquired as deterministic values. Dual uncertainties may be presented as fuzzy sets with known possibility distributions, whereas the others might be ex- pressed as intervals with known lower and upper bounds without knowing their membership functions and/or distributions. The con- ventional queuing and/or storage models have difficulties in response to such complexities.

In the real-world EPS, uncertainties exist among various energy purchase processes, electricity generation activities, and economic, technical and environmental indicators (Khooban et al., 2016; Cheng et al., 2017; Ammenberg et al., 2018; Jafari et al., 2018). For example, due to the subjective judgements of managers on when the vehicles should leave the waiting line, uncertainties existing in waiting time can be described as fuzzy sets (Sun et al., 2011). In addition, electricity demand, which is affected by population and economy, often cannot be derived as precise value. Fuzzy programming (FP) is effective for coping with ambiguous information in objective function and constraints (both left- and right-hand sides). Besides, interval-parameter programming (IPP) is an alternative for handling uncertainties in the model’s left- and/or right-hand sides as well as those that cannot be quantified as membership or distribution functions, since interval numbers are ac- ceptable as its uncertain inputs (Li et al., 2017). One potential approach to deal with the problems of queue and storage, as well as to tackle dual uncertainties existed in queue and storage is incorporating FP, IPP, queue and storage theories into a general framework. Therefore, the objective of this study is to develop an interval fuzzy queue-storage (IFQS) method for planning electric power systems (EPS). Through integrating interval-parameter programming (IPP), fuzzy programming (FP), queue and storage theories into a general framework, IFQS is useful for dealing with uncertainties in terms of fuzzy sets and interval values, as well as reflecting the behavior of dynamic systems. Then, IFQS will be applied to a real case of planning Shijiazhuang’s EPS where different storage periods are examined to investigate the impacts of purchase batches on EPS. Optimized solu- tions of coal purchase, power generation, pollutant-emission mitiga- tion, and system cost will be generated. Results will be helpful for generating coal-purchase and electricity-production plans as well as disclosing the impacts of queuing and storage on the EPS. 2. Development of IFQS-EPS model

In EPS management, queuing phenomenon has effects on the re- sources purchase process, and M/M/1 (exponential interarrival time, exponential service time and one server) queuing models can be in- troduced to handle the queuing problem. In the classical M/M/1 queuing model, both the interarrival time and service time are assumed to be independent exponential variables. The arrival number in a cer- tain time obeys the Poisson distribution (Sun et al., 2012; Haviv and Oz, 2016; Chen et al., 2017). The service time is independent and follows the same negative exponential distribution. Owing to human-induced or natural variability, a number of un- certainties exist among queuing phenomenon, economic activities and energy policies in EPS planning. For example, electricity demands are highly dependent on economic condition that fluctuates within a cer- tain range; electricity demand variation can result in changes in re- sources supply and electricity generation. Arrival and service rates of queuing problem are affected by decision makers’ subjective judgment, thus leading to different resource purchase schemes. Besides, un- certainties are presented in the EPS owing to variations of coal pur- chase, transportation and storage costs, power plants’ operation and maintain costs, and multi-pollutant emissions allowances. Based on the IFQS method, an IFQS-EPS model is formulated for EPS planning. In the IFQS-EPS model, the problems considered include how to: (i) determine the coal purchase in view of queuing and storage issues, (ii) arrange the plans for electricity generation and supply, (iii) achieve a minimum system cost under considering environmental constraint, and (iv) reflect dual uncertainties such as fuzzy sets and interval values. As shown in Fig. 1, the detailed solution process of solving the IFQS-EPS model can be summarized as: (1) formulate the IFQS-EPS model; (2) analyze the queuing system data, and select suitable queuing model (the M/M/1 model is chosen in this study); (3) fix the α-cut level and calculate the results of the M/M/1 queuing model; (4) introduce the results of queuing model and convert the IFQS-EPS model into a traditional IPP-EPS one; (5) transform the IPP-EPS model into two deterministic submodels based on an inter- active algorithm presented in Appendix B (Huang et al., 1992); (6) solve the submodel to obtain the solutions corresponding to the lower- bound objective-function value; (7) solve the submodel to obtain the solutions related to the upper-bound objective-function value; (8) in- terval solutions can be obtained through combining the results of two submodels under the fixed α-cut level; (9) repeat (3) - (8) at each T level and each α-cut; (10) analyze results and generate decision alternatives.

The City of Shijiazhuang is located in the southwest of Hebei pro- vince, which occupies an administrative area of around 15,848 km2. In 2016, Shijiazhuang’s GDP was $85.1 billion and accounted for 15.8% of the whole provincial GDP (ranking the second in Hebei province). The city’s electricity consumption was 46.3 × 103 GWh in 2016, which increased 12.1% compared with that in 2011. The city’s electricity supply mainly relies on coal-fired power plants. In 2005, the installed capacity of coal-fired power was around 3721 MW and occupied 97.5% in total installed capacity. However, as a region of scarce coal, local coal exploitation is far from meeting the city’s demand. The amount of coal supply from other provinces (mainly form Shanxi and Shaanxi provinces) was about 50.9 million ton per year; in comparison, the coal from local exploitation was only 0.6 million ton. Coal purchase from different and distant coal mines leads to differences in coal properties, purchase and transportation costs, as well as complicated queuing problems, thus resulting in varied schemes of electricity generation, system cost, and pollutant emission (Liu et al., 2018). In addition, coal purchase process is affected by storage period. Varied storage periods result in changed coal purchase batches and different purchase schemes. The massive consumption of coal has caused serious air pollution for the City of Shijiazhuang. In 2017, the mean concentrations of particu- late matter (PM) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) respectively were 154 μg/ m3 and 54 μg/m3, which were much higher than the concentration limits (i.e. 70 μg/m3 and 40 μg/m3, respectively) required by the National Ambient Air Quality Standards. occurred frequently and the day that the city’s air was polluted by haze was upward to 187 in 2016. Exposure to such serious air pollution has aggravated the mortality from respiratory and heart diseases. In order to improve the city’s environmental quality, coal-fired power plants are forced to largely reduce the emissions of multiple pollutants. A number of regulations were also issued by the local government which aimed at lessening the dependence of EPS on coal. Therefore, it is essential for Shijiazhuang to effectively plan its EPS with consideration of resource purchase, resource storage, energy conversion and pollutant mitigation. The city’s EPS consists of four subsystems, including resource pur- chase, resource storage, electricity generation and pollutant emission. In the subsystem of resource purchase, due to the lack of coal resource, imported coal plays a crucial role in total coal supply. Based on the related energy policies published by the government, coal mines in Yulin (YL), Datong (DT) and Jincheng (JC) which have high-quality coal are preferred to reduce pollutant emission from EPS. Moreover, according to statistics, the share of coal-fired power plant with capacity over 300 MW in total installed capacity is about 80% (Shijiazhuang Statistics Bureau, 2017). Thus, in the subsystem of electricity genera- tion, eight coal-fired power plants, whose capacity is over 300 MW, are mainly considered (as shown in Table 1). In addition, the city’s EPS is surrounded with various uncertainties which may affect the planning effort and decision making. For example, subjective judgments from different decision makers are often involved in coal purchase processes. Modeling inputs are estimated based on the local government official reports, statistical yearbooks or derived from published papers (Jin et al., 2018; Yu et al., 2018). 4.1. Waiting time of queuing system

Fig. 2 shows the probabilities of different arriving units in queuing system of coal purchase process. The curves indicate that the ratio of arrival rate and service rate is less than 1 and, thus, the queuing system could reach a steady-state condition and the solutions could be stable and robust. Fig. 3 presents the solutions for waiting time of the three coal mines under different α-cut levels. Results show that the waiting time would be narrower intervals with the rising of α-cut levels. For example, in period 1, the waiting time for coal mines in YL would be [1.67, 4.31] under α = 0 and [2.29, 2.66] day under α = 1. This is due to the fact that different α-cut levels correspond to different member- ship degrees of power plants’ average arrival rate and coal mines’ ser- vice rate in queues, resulting in changed waiting times. Meanwhile, with the improvement of production efficiency in coal mines, the waiting time would be less in periods 2 and 3. For instance, when α = 0, the waiting time for coal mines in DT would be respectively [1.84, 5.30] in period 1 and [1.63, 4.35] day in period 3. Besides, re- sults also indicate that the waiting time would be different from for coal mines in YL, DT and JC. Specially, in period 1 under α = 0, the waiting time of coal mines in YL, DT and JC would be respectively [1.67, 4.31], [1.84, 5.30] and [0.18, 0.82] day. Such a difference is due to the dis- crepancy in production capacity and sale quantity in per unit time of the three mines, leading to varied waiting times. The waiting time of coal mines in JC would be obviously shorter than those in YL and DT, because of the highest productivity of coal mines in JC. As a result, coal- fired power plants which wait in queues of coal mines in YL and DT have to purchase coal from coal mines in JC. 4.2. Coal purchase scheme

period 1 to 5506.46 GW h in period 2 (under T = 10). Such an incre- ment is due to the improvement of coal-fired technology, which reduces the coal consumption rate. Under the constraints of total coal amount, lower coal consumption rate leads to higher electricity generation. Meanwhile, to mitigate the air pollutant emissions, the amount of electricity generation (especially from coal-fired plants) would reduce. For instance, under T = 10, the lower bound of electricity generation from XBP2 would reduce from 5339.36 GW h in period 1 to 5328.29 GW h in period 2. The reduction of coal consumption and strict constraint of pollutant emissions would have an interactive effect on the EPS planning. Results demonstrate that the measures associated with reducing coal consumption rate and air pollutant emissions for per unit electricity, such as purchasing high quality coal and improving coal combustion and air pollutant control technologies, are critical for the city’s EPS to increase electricity generated by coal-fired power plants. Table 3 presents the electricity supply from some clean energies (i.e. natural gas, wind and solar), implying that electricity supply from clean energies would increase with time. For instance, when α = 0 and T = 10, electricity supply by clean energies would increase from [8616, 9246] GWh in period 1 to [11573, 11774] GWh in period 3. The share of electricity generated by clean energies would be increase from 20% to 25%. The reason is that, as time goes by, the technologies of clean electricity generation are improved and promote the progress of clean electricity generation. Another reason is that the limitations of coal supply and pollutant emissions would lead to the restriction of coal- fired electricity generation. Thus, except for the advance of clean en- ergy technologies, the policies for the requirement of air quality and the restriction of coal consumption are important for obtaining more rea- sonable electric power structure. 4.4. Pollutant-emission control

Fig. 9 shows solutions of pollutant emissions under different α-cut levels. Interval values of PM and NOx emissions would both be nar- rower with an increased α-cut; interval values of SO2 emission would have the opposite trend. For example, when T = 10, interval values of NOx would be [103.76, 124.85] t (α = 0) and [104.04, 123.96] × 103 t (α = 1); intervals of SO2 would be [28.09, 34.64] t (α = 0) and [27.55, 35.57] × 103 t (α = 1). It is due to the fact that different α-cut levels lead to changed waiting times and coal purchase plans. In the real case of Shijiazhuang, the coal has higher ash content, higher nitrogen con- tent and lower sulfur content in the coal mines which supply waiting or departure amount of coal. With the increased waiting time, the amount of SO2 emission for unit electricity decreases, while the amounts of PM and NOx emissions increase. Besides, NOx emission under T = 20 would be less than that under T = 10, while the majority of SO2 emission under T = 20 would be more than that under T = 10. It is attributed to the fact that shorter storage period leads to more queuing times and total waiting time, which brings about more NOx and less SO2 emis- sions. Due to high concentration of PM and NOx in Shijiazhuang, the reduction of waiting time that can be realized by purchasing more coal from routine coal mines with high productivity and increasing the storage amount and period, could reap huge fruits on air quality im- provement since more coal with low ash and low nitrogen content α = 0 α = 0.2 α = 0.5 α = 0.8 α = 1 [43.08, 46.23] [43.18, 45.95] [43.34, 45.71] [43.52, 45.52] [43.66, 45.40]

The system cost consists of the purchase and transportation fees of routine and departure coal, purchase and transportation fees of coal in waiting time (i.e. waiting cost), coal storage fee, electricity generation cost, pollutant emission reduction cost, pollutant emission charge, non- coal electricity supply cost, and environmental subsidy. Fig. 10 presents the details of waiting cost and system cost, indicating that the intervals of waiting cost and system cost would be narrower with the rising of α- cut. Both waiting cost and system cost would be higher under T = 10 than those under T = 20 because there are more batches for coal pur- chase under T = 10. Correspondingly, this can cause higher total waiting time and higher waiting cost. In addition, the increased total waiting time resulting in different coal purchase and electricity gen- eration patterns would bring about the increase of costs for coal pur- chase, electricity generation, air pollutant emission reduction and non- coal electricity supply. Although shorter storage period causes less coal storage cost, the storage cost is still far less than other costs for elec- tricity generation. Consequently, shorter storage period leads to higher system cost. Thus, less waiting time and longer storage period are beneficial for achieving lower system cost. 4.6. Comparison with interval fuzzy queue

Solutions of the IFQS-EPS model reveal an effective linkage among electricity generation, queue, storage and system cost. Without con- sidering storage period, the study problem can be formulated as an interval-fuzzy queue based EPS (abbreviated as IFQ-EPS) model. System costs from IFQ-EPS and IFQS-EPS are presented in Fig. 11. System cost from IFQ-EPS would be $[2.77, 4.20] ×109, higher than that from IFQS-EPS. The reason is the introduction of storage period avoids the losses caused by excessive coal purchase batches and waiting time. Table 4 shows annual electricity supply from coal would be higher than that with consideration of storage period; on the contrary, electricity supply from clean energies would decrease from IFQ-EPS. For example, when α = 0 and k = 1, the non-coal electricity supply from IFQ-EPS would be [51.54, 56.46] × 103 GWh, while the result from IFQS-EPS would be [43.08, 46.23] × 103 GWh (T = 10). This is mainly because of the overmuch use of poor-quality coal with lower calorific value and higher nitrogen content in IFQ-EPS. It would lead to more coal con- sumption and pollutant emissions (particularly for NOx) for per unit electricity generation, thus resulting in limitation of coal-fired elec- tricity generation. For example, when α = 0, the amount of NOx emission from IFQ-EPS would be [106.22, 128.47] × 103 t, and that from IFQS-EPS with more coal-fired generation would be [103.76, 124.85] × 103 t (T = 10). In general, compared with the IFQ-EPS model, the IFQS-EPS model has advantages in better reflecting the complexities of coal purchase queue and storage, reducing system cost and pollutant emission. Resources, Conservation & Recycling 145 (2019) 241–260 In this study, an interval fuzzy queue-storage (IFQS) method has been developed for planning electric power systems (EPS) under dual uncertainties. Through integrating interval-parameter programming (IPP), fuzzy programming (FP), queue and storage theories into a general framework, IFQS can tackle uncertainties presented in forms of both interval values and fuzzy sets. Meanwhile, IFQS can deal with queuing problem in resource purchase process and inspect the resource storage effects on EPS. Compared to interval-fuzzy queue (IFQ) ap- proach, the IFQS method can balance the conflict between coal pur- chase and storage period, and help decision makers obtain the optimal resource purchase and electricity generation plans with a minimum system cost. Then, an IFQS-EPS model has been formulated for the City Fig. 10. Solutions for cost under different α-cut levels [(a) purchasing and transporting coal cost in waiting time, (b) system cost].

of Shijiazhuang where M/M/1 (exponential interarrival time, ex- ponential service time and one server) queues are taken into account. A number of scenarios based on changed storage periods and α-cut levels have been examined to reveal the impacts of queuing and storage issues on EPS. Solutions regarding coal purchase, energy conversion, pollutant control, and system cost under different scenarios have been analyzed. Results disclose that: (i) the major coal suppliers for the study city are the coal mines in YL, DT and JC (providing over 77% of coal); (ii) the longer the waiting time is, the higher system cost is; and when the waiting time enhance 1 day, the system cost would add approximately $200 million; (iii) longer storage period leads to less coal purchase cost and less system cost, and compared with storage period of 20 day, system cost would increase $[210, 560] × 106 when storage period is 10 day; (iv) pollutant emissions (PM and NOx) would increase with Resources, Conservation & Recycling 145 (2019) 241–260 waiting time (e.g., NOx emission would add about 91 ton as waiting time raise 1 day; (v) electricity supply by clean energies would enhance 5% because of coal supply and pollutant emission restrictions; (vi) the system cost from IFQS-EPS is lower than that from IFQ-EPS and, at the same time, the electricity generated by coal from IFQ-EPS is less than Fig. 11. Solutions for system cost under different α-cut levels [(a) lower bound, (b) upper bound]. that from IFQS-EPS. The results are helpful for decision makers to formulate appropriate coal purchase and electricity generation plans, as well as gain insight into the effects of queuing problem and storage period on EPS under complex uncertainties.
